This paper is about a programming language that is based on the algebraic approach to computational effects. This approach is closely related to programming language theory and semantics, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. The paper also discusses the denotational semantics of the language, which is a formal method for describing the meaning of programs, indicating that it could also belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses a prototype implementation of the language, which suggests that it could belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper also discusses various programming techniques that use delimited continuations, which are closely related to data structures and algorithms, suggesting that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the standard effects that are treated in the language, which suggests that it could belong to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category.
